"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is crucial for 3D vision, but accurately recovering depth in non-Lambertian regions remains a formidable challenge due to the violation of photo-consistency assumptions. Existing epipolar plane image (EPI) methods severely degrade in these regions, often mistaking specular textures for depth structures and producing texture-copying artifacts. To address this, a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model was proposed, integrating physically interpretable material classification with component-aware depth regression. Specifically, a dual-mask mechanism was introduced, and a 2D discrete Fourier transform was applied on angular samples to classify materials via frequency energy distribution. Furthermore, a simplified Cook-Torrance BRDF model extracted physical parameters to facilitate guided training for a component-aware fusion strategy, adaptively assigning optimal geometric constraints for diffuse, specular, and scattering regions. Additionally, a triplet-mask adaptive energy adjustment utilizing a geometric consistency descriptor was designed to eliminate smooth artifacts. Extensive experiments demonstrate that the lightweight network achieves an overall mean absolute error of 0.1415, significantly outperforming traditional EPI baselines that fail in non-Lambertian domains (MAE 0.411). Moreover, the adaptive energy adjustment boosts the depth contrast ratio by up to 33.8 times in complex scenes. Ultimately, this work bridges physical reflectance modeling and deep learning, providing a robust and physically grounded solution for mixed-material light field depth estimation.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance, Dual-mask physical model, Angular frequency analysis, BRDF parameter fitting, Component-aware fusion"